d woman\a146s outfit,\a148 he said.\a147But what is it all about, Billy?\a148Billy sank his voice, as one who discusses great secrets of State. \a147I don\a146t mind telling you, sir, but it should go no farther. It\a146s this case of the Crown diamond.\a148\a147What\a151 the hundred-thousand-pound burglary?\a148\a147Yes, sir. They must get it back, sir. Why, we had the Prime Minister and the Home Secretary both sitting on that very sofa. Mr. Holmes was very nice to them. He soon put them at their ease and promised he would do all he could. Then there is Lord Cantlemere\a151\a148\a147Ah!\a148\a147Yes, sir, you know what that means. He\a146s a stiff\a146un, sir, if I may say so. I can get along with the Prime Minister, and I\a146ve nothing against the Home Secretary, who seemed a civil, obliging sort of man, but I can\a146t stand his Lordship. Neither can Mr. Holmes, sir. You see, he don\a146t believe in Mr. Holmes and he was against employing him. He\a146d rather he failed.\a148\a147And Mr. Holmes knows it?\a148\a147Mr. Holmes always knows whatever there is to know.\a148\a147Well, we\a146ll hope he won\a146t fail and that Lord Cantlemere will be confounded. But I say, Billy, what is that curtain for across the window?\a148\a147Mr. Holmes had it put up there three days ago. We\a146ve got something funny behind it.\a148Billy advanced and drew away the drapery which screened the alcove of the bow window.Dr. Watson could not restrain a cry of amazement. There was a facsimile of his old friend, dressing-gown and all, the face turned three-quarters towards the window and downward, as though reading an invisible book, while the body was sunk deep in an armchair. Billy detached the head and held it in the air.\a147We put it at different angles, so that it may seem more lifelike. I wouldn\a146t dare touch it if the blind were not down. But when it\a146s up you can see this from across the way.\a148\a147We used something of the sort once before.\a148\a147Before my time,\a148 said Billy. He drew the window curtains apart and looked out into the street. \a147There are folk who watch us from over yonder. I can see a fellow now at the window. Have a look for yourself.\a148Watson had taken a step forward when the bedroom door opened, and the long, thin form of Holmes emerged, his face pale and drawn, but his step and bearing as active as ever. With a single spring he was at the window, and had drawn the blind once more.\a147That will do, Billy,\a148 said he. \a147You were in danger of your life then, my boy, and I can\a146t do without you just yet. Well, Watson, it is good to see you in your old quarters once again. You come at a critical moment.\a148\a147So I gather.\a148\a147You can go, Billy. That boy is a problem, Watson. How far am I justified in allowing him to be in danger?\a148\a147Danger of what, Holmes?\a148\a147Of sudden death. I\a146m expecting something this evening.\a148\a147Expecting what?\a148\a147To be murdered, Watson.\a148\a147No, no, you are joking, Holmes!\a148\a147Even my limited sense of humour could evolve a better joke than that. But we may be comfortable in the meantime, may we not? Is alcohol permitted? The gasogene and cigars are in the old place. Let me see you once more in the customary armchair. You have not, I hope, learned to despise my pipe and my lamentable tobacco? It has to take the place of food these days.\a148\a147But why not eat?\a148\a147Because the faculties become refined when you starve them. Why, surely, as a doctor, my dear Watson, you must admit that what your digestion gains in the way of blood supply is so much lost to the brain. I am a brain, Watson. The rest of me is a mere appendix. Therefore, it is the brain I must consider.\a148\a147But this danger, Holmes?\a148\a147Ah, yes, in case it should come off, it would perhaps be as well that you should burden your memory with the name and address of the murderer. You can give it to Scotland Yard, with my love and a parting blessing. Sylvius is the name\a151 Count Negretto Sylvius. Write it down, man, write it down! 136 Moorside Gardens, N. W. Got it?\a148Watson\a146s honest face was twitching with anxiety. He knew only too well the immense risks taken by Holmes and was well aware that what he said was more likely to be under-statement than exaggeration. Watson was always the man of action, and he rose to the occasion.\a147Count me in, Holmes. I have nothing to do for a day or two.\a148\a147Your morals don\a146t improve, Watson. You have added fibbing to your other vices. You bear every sign of the busy medical man, with calls on him every hour.\a148\a147Not such important ones. But can\a146t you have this fellow arrested?\a148\a147Yes, Watson, I could. That\a146s what worries him so.\a148\a147But why don\a146t you?\a148\a147Because I don\a146t know where the diamond is.\a148\a147Ah! Billy told me\a151 the missing Crown jewel!\a148\a147Yes, the great yellow Mazarin stone. I\a146ve cast my net and I have my fish. But I have not got the stone. What is the use of taking them? We can make the world a better place by laying them by the heels. But that is not what I am out for. It\a146s the stone I want.\a148\a147And is this Count Sylvius one of your fish?\a148\a147Yes, and he\a146s a shark. He bites. The other is Sam Merton the boxer. Not a bad fellow, Sam, but the Count has used him. Sam\a146s not a shark. He is a great big silly bull-headed gudgeon. But he is flopping about in my net all the same.\a148\a147Where is this Count Sylvius?\a148\a147I\a146ve been at his very elbow all the morning. You\a146ve seen me as an old lady, Watson. I was never more convincing. He actually picked up my parasol for me once. \a145By your leave, madame,\a146 said he\a151 half-ltalian, you know, and with the Southern graces of manner when in the mood, but a devil incarnate in the other mood. Life is full of whimsical happenings, Watson.\a148\a147It might have been tragedy.\a148\a147Well, perhaps it might. I followed him to old Straubenzee\a146s workshop in the Minories. Straubenzee made the air-gun\a151 a very pretty bit of work, as I understand, and I rather fancy it is in the opposite window at the present moment. Have you seen the dummy? Of course, Billy showed it to you. Well, it may get a bullet through its beautiful head at any moment. Ah, Billy, what is it?\a148The boy had reappeared in the room with a card upon a tray. Holmes glanced at it with raised eyebrows and an amused smile.\a147The man himself. I had hardly expected this. Grasp the nettle, Watson! A man of nerve. Possibly you have heard of his reputation as a shooter of big game. It would indeed be a triumphant ending to his excellent sporting record if he added me to his bag. This is a proof that he feels my toe very close behind his heel.\a148\a147Send for the police.\a148\a147I probably shall. But not just yet. Would you glance carefully out of the window, Watson, and see if anyone is hanging about in the street?\a148Watson looked warily round the edge of the curtain.\a147Yes, there is one rough fellow near the door.\a148\a147That will be Sam Merton\a151 the faithful but rather fatuous Sam. Where is this gentleman, Billy?\a148\a147In the waiting-room, sir.\a148\a147Show him up when I ring.\a148\a147Yes, sir.\a148\a147If I am not in the room, show him in all the same.\a148\a147Yes, sir.\a148Watson waited until the door was closed, and then he turned earnestly to his companion.\a147Look here, Holmes, this is simply impossible. This is a desperate man, who sticks at nothing. He may have come to murder you.\a148\a147I should not be surprised.\a148\a147I insist upon staying with you.\a148\a147You would be horribly in the way.\a148\a147In his way?\a148\a147No, my dear fellow\a151 in my way.\a148\a147Well, I can\a146t possibly leave you.\a148\a147Yes, you can, Watson. And you will, for you have never failed to play the game. I am sure you will play it to the end. This man has come for his own purpose, but he may stay for mine.\a148Holmes took out his notebook and scribbled a few lines. \a147Take a cab to Scotland Yard and give this to Youghal of the C. I. D. Come back with the police. The fellow\a146s arrest will follow.\a148\a147I\a146ll do that with joy.\a147Before you return I may have just time enough to find out where the stone is.\a148 He touched the bell. \a147I think we will go out through the bedroom. This second exit is exceedingly useful. I rather want to see my shark without his seeing me, and I have, as you will remember, my own way of doing it.\a148It was, therefore, an empty room into which Billy, a minute later, ushered Count Sylvius. The famous game-shot, sportsman, and man-about-town was a big, swarthy fellow, with a formidable dark moustache shading a cruel, thin-lipped mouth, and surmounted by a long, curved nose like the beak of an eagle. He was well dressed, but his brilliant necktie, shining pin, and glittering rings were flamboyant in their effect. As the door closed behind him he looked round him with fierce, startled eyes, like one who suspects a trap at every turn. Then he gave a violent start as he saw the impassive head and the collar of the dressing-gown which projected above the armchair in the window. At first his expression was one of pure amazement. Then the light of a horrible hope gleamed in his dark, murderous eyes. He took one more glance round to see that there were no witnesses, and then, on tiptoe, his thick stick half raised, he approached the silent figure. He was crouching for his final spring and blow when a cool, sardonic voice greeted him from the open bedroom door:\a147Don\a146t break it, Count! Don\a146t break it!\a148The assassin staggered back, amazement in his convulsed face. For an instant he half raised his loaded cane once more, as if he would turn his violence from the effigy to the original; but there was something in that steady gray eye and mocking smile which caused his hand to sink to his side.\a147It\a146s a pretty little thing,\a148 said Holmes, advancing towards the image. \a147Tavernier, the French modeller, made it. He is as good at waxworks as your friend Straubenzee is at air-guns.\a148\a147Air-guns, sir! What do you mean?\a148\a147Put your hat and stick on the side-table. Thank you! Pray take a seat. Would you care to put your revolver out also? Oh, very good, if you prefer to sit upon it. Your visit is really most opportune, for I wanted badly to have a few minutes\a146 chat with you. \a148The Count scowled, with heavy, threatening eyebrows.\a147I, too, wished to have some words with you, Holmes. That is why I am here. I won\a146t deny that I intended to assault you just now.\a148Holmes swung his leg on the edge of the table.\a147I rather gathered that you had some idea of the sort in your head,\a148 said he. \a147But why these personal attentions?\a148\a147Because you have gone out of your way to annoy me. Because you have put your creatures upon my track.\a148\a147My creatures! I assure you no!\a148\a147Nonsense! I have had them followed. Two can play at that game, Holmes.\a148\a147It is a small point, Count Sylvius, but perhaps you would kindly give me my prefix when you address me. You can understand that, with my routine of work, I should find myself on familiar terms with half the rogues\a146 gallery, and you will agree that exceptions are invidious.\a148\a147Well, \iMr\i Holmes, then.\a148\a147Excellent! But I assure you you are mistaken about my alleged agents.\a148Count Sylvius laughed contemptuously.\a147Other people can observe as well as you. Yesterday there was an old sporting man. To-day it was an elderly woman. They held me in view all day.\a148\a147Really, sir, you compliment me. Old Baron Dowson said the night before he was hanged that in my case what the law had gained the stage had lost. And now you give my little impersonations your kindly praise?\a148\a147It was you\a151 you yourself?\a148Holmes shrugged his shoulders. \a147You can see in the corner the parasol which you so politely handed to me in the Minories before you began to suspect.\a148\a147If I had known, you might never\a151\a148\a147Have seen this humble home again. I was well aware of it. We all have neglected opportunities to deplore. As it happens, you did not know, so here we are!\a148The Count\a146s knotted brows gathered more heavily over his menacing eyes. \a147What you say only makes the matter worse. It was not your agents but your play-acting, busybody self! You admit that you have dogged me. Why?\a148\a147Come now, Count. You used to shoot lions in Algeria.\a148\a147Well?\a148\a147But why?\a148\a147Why? The sport\a151 the excitement\a151 the danger!\a148\a147And, no doubt, to free the country from a pest?\a148\a147Exactly!\a148\a147My reasons in a nutshell!\a148The Count sprang to his feet, and his hand involuntarily moved back to his hip-pocket.\a147Sit down, sir, sit down! There was another, more practical, reason. I want that yellow diamond!\a148Count Sylvius lay back in his chair with an evil smile.\a147Upon my word!\a148 said he.\a147You knew that I was after you for that. The real reason why you are here to-night is to find out how much I know about the matter and how far my removal is absolutely essential. Well, I should say that, from your point of view, it is absolutely essential, for I know all about it, save only one thing, which you are about to tell me.\a148\a147Oh, indeed! And pray, what is this missing fact?\a148\a147Where the Crown diamond now is.\a148The Count looked sharply at his companion. \a147Oh, you want to know that, do you? How the devil should I be able to tell you where it is?\a148\a147You can, and you will.\a148\a147Indeed!\a148\a147You can\a146t bluff me, Count Sylvius.\a148 Holmes\a146s eyes, as he gazed at him, contracted and lightened until they were like two menacing points of steel. \a147You are absolute plate-glass. I see to the very back of your mind.\a148\a147Then, of course, you see where the diamond is!\a148Holmes clapped his hands with amusement, and then pointed a derisive finger. \a147Then you do know. You have admitted it!\a148\a147I admit nothing.\a148\a147Now, Count, if you will be reasonable we can do business. If not, you will get hurt.\a148Count Sylvius threw up his eyes to the ceiling. \a147And you talk about bluff!\a148 said he.Holmes looked at him thoughtfully like a master chess-player who meditates his crowning move. Then he threw open the table drawer and drew out a squat notebook.\a147Do you know what I keep in this book?\a148\a147No, sir, I do not!\a148\a147You!\a148\a147Me!\a148\a147Yes, sir, you! You are all here\a151 every action of your vile and dangerous life.\a148\a147Damn you, Holmes!\a148 cried the Count with blazing eyes. \a147There are limits to my patience!\a148\a147It\a146s all here, Count. The real facts as to the death of old Mrs. Harold, who left you the Blymer estate, which you so rapidly gambled away.\a148\a147You are dreaming!\a148\a147And the complete life history of Miss Minnie Warrender.\a148\a147Tut! You will make nothing of that!\a148\a147Plenty more here, Count. Here is the robbery in the train de-luxe to the Riviera on February 13, 1892. Here is the forged cheque in the same year on the Credit Lyonnais.\a148\a147No, you\a146re wrong there.\a148\a147Then I am right on the others! Now, Count, you are a card-player. When the other fellow has all the trumps, it saves time to throw down your hand.\a148\a147What has all this talk to do with the jewel of which you spoke?\a148\a147Gently, Count. Restrain that eager mind! Let me get to the points in my own humdrum fashion. I have all this against you; but, above all, I have a clear case against both you and your fighting bully in the case of the Crown diamond.\a148\a147Indeed!\a148\a147I have the cabman who took you to Whitehall and the cabman who brought you away. I have the commissionaire who saw you near the case. I have Ikey Sanders, who refused to cut it up for you. Ikey has peached, and the game is up.\a148The veins stood out on the Count\a146s forehead. His dark, hairy hands were clenched in a convulsion of restrained emotion. He tried to speak, but the words would not shape themselves.\a147That\a146s the hand I play from,\a148 said Holmes. \a147I put it all upon the table. But one card is missing. It\a146s the king of diamonds. I don\a146t know where the stone is.\a148\a147You never shall know.\a148\a147No? Now, be reasonable, Count. Consider the situation. You are going to be locked up for twenty years. So is Sam Merton. What good are you going to get out of your diamond? None in the world. But if you hand it over\a151 well, I\a146ll compound a felony. We don\a146t want you or Sam. We want the stone. Give that up, and so far as I am concerned you can go free so long as you behave yourself in the future. If you make another slip well, it will be the last. But this time my commission is to get the stone, not you.\a148\a147But if I refuse?\a148\a147Why, then\a151 alas!\a151 it must be you and not the stone.\a148Billy had appeared in answer to a ring.\a147I think, Count, that it would be as well to have your friend Sam at this conference. After all, his interests should be represented. Billy, you will see a large and ugly gentleman outside the front door. Ask him to come up.\a148\a147If he won\a146t come, sir?\a148\a147No violence, Billy. Don\a146t be rough with him. If you tell him that Count Sylvius wants him he will certainly come.\a148\a147What are you going to do now?\a148 asked the Count as Billy disappeared.\a147My friend Watson was with me just now. I told him that I had a shark and a gudgeon in my net; now I am drawing the net and up they come together.\a148The Count had risen from his chair, and his hand was behind his back. Holmes held something half protruding from the pocket of his dressing-gown.\a147You won\a146t die in your bed, Holmes.\a148\a147I have often had the same idea. Does it matter very much? After all, Count, your own exit is more likely to be perpendicular than horizontal. But these anticipations of the future are morbid. Why not give ourselves up to the unrestrained enjoyment of the present?\a148A sudden wild-beast light sprang up in the dark, menacing eyes of the master criminal. Holmes\a146s figure seemed to grow taller as he grew tense and ready.\a147It is no use your fingering your revolver, my friend,\a148 he said in a quiet voice. \a147You know perfectly well that you dare not use it, even if I gave you time to draw it. Nasty, noisy things, revolvers, Count. Better stick to air-guns. Ah! I think I hear the fairy footstep of your estimable partner. Good day, Mr. Merton. Rather dull in the street, is it not?\a148The prize-fighter, a heavily built young man with a stupid, obstinate, slab-sided face, stood awkwardly at the door, looking about him with a puzzled expression. Holmes\a146s debonair manner was a new experience, and though he vaguely felt that it was hostile, he did not know how to counter it. He turned to his more astute comrade for help.\a147What\a146s the game now, Count? What\a146s this fellow want? What\a146s up?\a148 His voice was deep and raucous.The Count shrugged his shoulders, and it was Holmes who answered.\a147If I may put it in a nutshell, Mr. Merton, I should say it was all up.\a148The boxer still addressed his remarks to his associate.\a147Is this cove trying to be funny, or what? I\a146m not in the funny mood myself.\a148\a147No, I expect not,\a148 said Holmes. \a147I think I can promise you that you will feel even less humorous as the evening advances. Now, look here, Count Sylvius. I\a146m a busy man and I can\a146t waste time. I\a146m going into that bedroom. Pray make yourselves quite at home in my absence. You can explain to your friend how the matter lies without the restraint of my presence. I shall try over the Hoffman \a145Barcarole\a146 upon my violin. In five minutes I shall return for your final answer. You quite grasp the alternative, do you not? Shall we take you, or shall we have the stone?\a148Holmes withdrew, picking up his violin from the corner as he passed. A few moments later the long-drawn, wailing notes of that most haunting of tunes came faintly through the closed door of the bedroom.\a147What is it, then?\a148 asked Merton anxiously as his companion turned to him. \a147Does he know about the stone?\a148\a147He knows a damned sight too much about it. I\a146m not sure that he doesn\a146t know all about it.\a148\a147Good Lord!\a148 The boxer\a146s sallow face turned a shade whiter.\a147Ikey Sanders has split on us.\a148\a147He has, has he? I\a146ll do him down a thick \a146un for that if I swing for it.\a148\a147That won\a146t help us much. We\a146ve got to make up our minds what to do.\a148\a147Half a mo\a146,\a148 said the boxer, looking suspiciously at the bedroom door. \a147He\a146s a leary cove that wants watching. I suppose he\a146s not listening?\a148\a147How can he be listening with that music going?\a148\a147That\a146s right. Maybe somebody\a146s behind a curtain. Too many curtains in this room.\a148 As he looked round he suddenly saw for the first time the effigy in the window, and stood staring and pointing, too amazed for words.\a147Tut! it\a146s only a dummy,\a148 said the Count.\a147A fake, is it? Well, strike me! Madame Tussaud ain\a146t in it. It\a146s the living spit of him, gown and all. But them curtains Count!\a148\a147Oh, confound the curtains! We are wasting our time, and there is none too much. He can lag us over this stone.\a148\a147The deuce he can!\a148\a147But he\a146ll let us slip if we only tell him where the swag is.\a148\a147What! Give it up? Give up a hundred thousand quid?\a148\a147It\a146s one or the other.\a148Merton scratched his short-cropped pate.\a147He\a146s alone in there. Let\a146s do him in. If his light were out we should have nothing to fear.\a148The Count shook his head.\a147He is armed and ready. If we shot him we could hardly get away in a place like this. Besides, it\a146s likely enough that the police know whatever evidence he has got. Hallo! What was that?\a148There was a vague sound which seemed to come from the window. Both men sprang round, but all was quiet. Save for the one strange figure seated in the chair, the room was certainly empty.\a147Something in the street,\a148 said Merton. \a147Now look here, guv\a146nor, you\a146ve got the brains. Surely you can think a way out of it. If slugging is no use then it\a146s up to you.\a148\a147I\a146ve fooled better men than he,\a148 the Count answered. \a147The stone is here in my secret pocket. I take no chances leaving it about. It can be out of England to-night and cut into four pieces in Amsterdam before Sunday. He knows nothing of Van Seddar.\a148\a147I thought Van Seddar was going next week.\a148\a147He was. But now he must get off by the next boat. One or other of us must slip round with the stone to Lime Street and tell him.\a148\a147But the false bottom ain\a146t ready.\a148\a147Well, he must take it as it is and chance it. There\a146s not a moment to lose.\a148 Again, with the sense of danger which becomes an instinct with the sportsman, he paused and looked hard at the window. Yes, it was surely from the street that the faint sound had come.\a147As to Holmes,\a148 he continued, \a147we can fool him easily enough. You see, the damned fool won\a146t arrest us if he can get the stone. Well, we\a146ll promise him the stone. We\a146ll put him on the wrong track about it, and before he finds that it is the wrong track it will be in Holland and we out of the country.\a148\a147That sounds good to me!\a148 cried Sam Merton with a grin.\a147You go on and tell the Dutchman to get a move on him. I\a146ll see this sucker and fill him up with a bogus confession. I\a146ll tell him that the stone is in Liverpool. Confound that whining music; it gets on my nerves! By the time he finds it isn\a146t in Liverpool it will be in quarters and we on the blue water. Come back here, out of a line with that keyhole. Here is the stone.\a148\a147I wonder you dare carry it.\a148\a147Where could I have it safer? If we could take it out of Whitehall someone else could surely take it out of my lodgings.\a148\a147Let\a146s have a look at it.\a148Count Sylvius cast a somewhat unflattering glance at his associate and disregarded the unwashed hand which was extended towards him.\a147What\a151 d\a146ye think I\a146m going to snatch it off you? See here, mister, I\a146m getting a bit tired of your ways.\a148\a147Well, well, no offence, Sam. We can\a146t afford to quarrel. Come over to the window if you want to see the beauty properly. Now hold it to the light! Here!\a148\a147Thank you!\a148With a single spring Holmes had leaped from the dummy\a146s chair and had grasped the precious jewel. He held it now in one hand, while his other pointed a revolver at the Count\a146s head. The two villains staggered back in utter amazement. Before they had recovered Holmes had pressed the electric bell.\a147No violence, gentlemen\a151 no violence, I beg of you! Consider the furniture! It must be very clear to you that your position is an impossible one. The police are waiting below.\a148The Count\a146s bewilderment overmastered his rage and fear.\a147But how the deuce\a151?\a148 he gasped.\a147Your surprise is very natural. You are not aware that a second door from my bedroom leads behind that curtain. I fancied that you must have heard me when I displaced the figure, but luck was on my side. It gave me a chance of listening to your racy conversation which would 