brought him the fewest personal opportunities, and it is one of these which I now desire to record. In telling it, I have made a slight change of name and place, but otherwise the facts are as stated.One forenoon\a151 it was late in 1896I received a hurried note from Holmes asking for my attendance. When I arrived I found him seated in a smoke-laden atmosphere, with an elderly, motherly woman of the buxom landlady type in the corresponding chair in front of him.\a147This is Mrs. Merrilow, of South Brixton,\a148 said my friend with a wave of the hand. \a147Mrs. Merrilow does not object to tobacco, Watson, if you wish to indulge your filthy habits. Mrs. Merrilow has an interesting story to tell which may well lead to further developments in which your presence may be useful.\a148\a147Anything I can do\a151\a148\a147You will understand, Mrs. Merrilow, that if I come to Mrs. Ronder I should prefer to have a witness. You will make her understand that before we arrive.\a148\a147Lord bless you, Mr. Holmes,\a148 said our visitor, \a147she is that anxious to see you that you might bring the whole parish at your heels!\a148\a147Then we shall come early in the afternoon. Let us see that we have our facts correct before we start. If we go over them it will help Dr. Watson to understand the situation. You say that Mrs. Ronder has been your lodger for seven years and that you have only once seen her face.\a148\a147And I wish to God I had not!\a148 said Mrs. Merrilow.\a147It was, I understand, terribly mutilated.\a148\a147Well, Mr. Holmes, you would hardly say it was a face at all. That\a146s how it looked. Our milkman got a glimpse of her once peeping out of the upper window, and he dropped his tin and the milk all over the front garden. That is the kind of face it is. When I saw her\a151 I happened on her unawares\a151 she covered up quick, and then she said, \a145Now, Mrs. Merrilow, you know at last why it is that I never raise my veil.\a146\a160\a148\a147Do you know anything about her history?\a148\a147Nothing at all.\a148\a147Did she give references when she came?\a148\a147No, sir, but she gave hard cash, and plenty of it. A quarter\a146s rent right down on the table in advance and no arguing about terms. In these times a poor woman like me can\a146t afford to turn down a chance like that.\a148\a147Did she give any reason for choosing your house?\a148\a147Mine stands well back from the road and is more private than most. Then, again, I only take the one, and I have no family of my own. I reckon she had tried others and found that mine suited her best. It\a146s privacy she is after, and she is ready to pay for it.\a148\a147You say that she never showed her face from first to last save on the one accidental occasion. Well, it is a very remarkable story, most remarkable, and I don\a146t wonder that you want it examined.\a148\a147I don\a146t, Mr. Holmes. I am quite satisfied so long as I get my rent. You could not have a quieter lodger, or one who gives less trouble.\a148\a147Then what has brought matters to a head?\a148\a147Her health, Mr. Holmes. She seems to be wasting away. And there\a146s something terrible on her mind. \a145Murder!\a146 she cries. \a145Murder!\a146 And once I heard her: \a145You cruel beast! You monster!\a146 she cried. It was in the night, and it fair rang through the house and sent the shivers through me. So I went to her in the morning. \a145Mrs. Ronder,\a146 I says, \a145if you have anything that is troubling your soul, there\a146s the clergy,\a146 I says, \a145and there\a146s the police. Between them you should get some help.\a146 \a145For God\a146s sake, not the police!\a146 says she, \a145and the clergy can\a146t change what is past. And yet,\a146 she says, \a145it would ease my mind if someone knew the truth before I died.\a146 \a145Well,\a146 says I, \a145if you won\a146t have the regulars, there is this detective man what we read about\a146beggin\a146 your pardon, Mr. Holmes. And she, she fair jumped at it. \a145That\a146s the man,\a146 says she. \a145I wonder I never thought of it before. Bring him here, Mrs. Merrilow, and if he won\a146t come, tell him I am the wife of Ronder\a146s wild beast show. Say that, and give him the name Abbas Parva. Here it is as she wrote it, Abbas Parva. \a145That will bring him if he\a146s the man I think he is.\a146\a160\a148\a147And it will, too,\a148 remarked Holmes. \a147Very good, Mrs. Merrilow. I should like to have a little chat with Dr. Watson. That will carry us till lunch-time. About three o\a146clock you may expect to see us at your house in Brixton.\a148Our visitor had no sooner waddled out of the room\a151 no other verb can describe Mrs. Merrilow\a146s method of progression\a151 than Sherlock Holmes threw himself with fierce energy upon the pile of commonplace books in the corner. For a few minutes there was a constant swish of the leaves, and then with a grunt of satisfaction he came upon what he sought. So excited was he that he did not rise, but sat upon the floor like some strange Buddha, with crossed legs, the huge books all round him, and one open upon his knees.\a147The case worried me at the time, Watson. Here are my marginal notes to prove it. I confess that I could make nothing of it. And yet I was convinced that the coroner was wrong. Have you no recollection of the Abbas Parva tragedy?\a148\a147None, Holmes.\a148\a147And yet you were with me then. But certainly my own impression was very superficial. For there was nothing to go by, and none of the parties had engaged my services. Perhaps you would care to read the papers?\a148\a147Could you not give me the points?\a148\a147That is very easily done. It will probably come back to your memory as I talk. Ronder, of course, was a household word. He was the rival of Wombwell, and of Sanger, one of the greatest showmen of his day. There is evidence, however, that he took to drink, and that both he and his show were on the down grade at the time of the great tragedy. The caravan had halted for the night at Abbas Parva, which is a small village in Berkshire, when this horror occurred. They were on their way to Wimbledon, travelling by road, and they were simply camping and not exhibiting, as the place is so small a one that it would not have paid them to open.\a147They had among their exhibits a very fine North African lion. Sahara King was its name, and it was the habit, both of Ronder and his wife, to give exhibitions inside its cage. Here, you see, is a photograph of the performance by which you will perceive that Ronder was a huge porcine person and that his wife was a very magnificent woman. It was deposed at the inquest that there had been some signs that the lion was dangerous, but, as usual, familiarity begat contempt, and no notice was taken of the fact.\a147It was usual for either Ronder or his wife to feed the lion at night. Sometimes one went, sometimes both, but they never allowed anyone else to do it, for they believed that so long as they were the food-carriers he would regard them as benefactors and would never molest them. On this particular night, seven years ago, they both went, and a very terrible happening followed, the details of which have never been made clear.\a147It seems that the whole camp was roused near midnight by the roars of the animal and the screams of the woman. The different grooms and employees rushed from their tents, carrying lanterns, and by their light an awful sight was revealed. Ronder lay, with the back of his head crushed in and deep claw-marks across his scalp, some ten yards from the cage, which was open. Close to the door of the cage lay Mrs. Ronder upon her back, with the creature squatting and snarling above her. It had torn her face in such a fashion that it was never thought that she could live. Several of the circus men, headed by Leonardo, the strong man, and Griggs, the clown, drove the creature off with poles, upon which it sprang back into the cage and was at once locked in. How it had got loose was a mystery. It was conjectured that the pair intended to enter the cage, but that when the door was loosed the creature bounded out upon them. There was no other point of interest in the evidence save that the woman in a delirium of agony kept screaming, \a145Coward! Coward!\a146 as she was carried back to the van in which they lived. It was six months before she was fit to give evidence, but the inquest was duly held, with the obvious verdict of death from misadventure.\a148\a147What alternative could be conceived?\a148 said I.\a147You may well say so. And yet there were one or two points which worried young Edmunds, of the Berkshire Constabulary. A smart lad that! He was sent later to Allahabad. That was how I came into the matter, for he dropped in and smoked a pipe or two over it.\a148\a147A thin, yellow-haired man?\a148\a147Exactly. I was sure you would pick up the trail presently.\a148\a147But what worried him?\a148\a147Well, we were both worried. It was so deucedly difficult to reconstruct the affair. Look at it from the lion\a146s point of view. He is liberated. What does he do? He takes half a dozen bounds forward, which brings him to Ronder. Ronder turns to fly\a151 the claw-marks were on the back of his head\a151 but the lion strikes him down. Then, instead of bounding on and escaping, he returns to the woman, who was close to the cage, and he knocks her over and chews her face up. Then, again, those cries of hers would seem to imply that her husband had in some way failed her. What could the poor devil have done to help her? You see the difficulty?\a148\a147Quite.\a148\a147And then there was another thing. It comes back to me now as I think it over. There was some evidence that just at the time the lion roared and the woman screamed, a man began shouting in terror.\a148\a147This man Ronder, no doubt.\a148\a147Well, if his skull was smashed in you would h